e given to learning materials that are shared in a way that encourages others to reuse and adapt them to new audiences.<\/p>\n<p>One of the most notable examples of an OER is Wikipedia, an encyclopaedia made possible by thousands of voluntary editors world-wide.<\/p>\n<p>OER have been well described by academics and advocates of open learning including <a href=\"http:\/\/davidwiley.org\/\">David Wiley<\/a> and <a href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lawrence_Lessig\">Laurence Lessig<\/a>. Both authors outline the importance of explicitly labelling resources with licences which promote the re-purposing and re-working.\u00a0They outline the fundamental characteristics of open licences and create frameworks and document case studies to facilitate their uptake.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>The internet has sparked an abundance of sharing of resources freely. From primary school teachers, to professors and undergraduate students sharing happens at all levels. By the end of this project you will have created and shared a learning resource online. MMU tutors can help you with this process. Creating and sharing a learning resource [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":66,"featured_media":0,"comment_status":"closed","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[128,129],"tags":[],"yoast_head":"<!-- This site is optimized with the Yoast SEO plugin v15.6.2 - https:\/\/yoast.com\/wordpress\/plugins\/seo\/ -->\n<meta name=\"robots\" content=\"index, follow, max-snippet:-1, max-image-preview:large, max-video-preview:-1\" \/>\n<link rel=\"canonical\" href=\"https:\/\/mcrblogs.co.uk\/edlab\/resource-creation-template-to-be-written\/\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:locale\" content=\"en_GB\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:type\" content=\"article\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:title\" content=\"EdLab Spark: Open Learning Resource Creation - EdLab MMU\" \/>\n<meta property=\"og:description\" content=\"The interne